          "title": "The kingdom's economics — resurrection-day repayment (12-14)",
          "body": "Jesus turns from the guests to the host. The Greco-Roman dinner system ran on reciprocity: you invited those who could invite you back; the meal generated and discharged social debt. Jesus dismantles that economy. *When you give a reception, invite the poor, the crippled, the lame, the blind* (v. 13) — precisely those whose presence would defile a Pharisaic table (cf. 2 Samuel 5:8 LXX traditions; Qumran's exclusion of the maimed from the eschatological banquet, 1QSa 2:5-22). The reward shifts from horizontal social return to vertical eschatological repayment: *you will be repaid at the resurrection of the righteous* (v. 14). The kingdom does not abolish accounting; it relocates the books to the resurrection. This is Jesus' answer to the *cui bono* question of every act of generosity — and it presupposes a bodily resurrection in which God Himself settles accounts."
