          "body": "The scene shifts (v. 25): Jesus leaves the Pharisee's house and turns to the *large crowds* walking with Him. He has prosecuted the religious establishment; now He filters the enthusiasts. Three times the refrain falls: *cannot be My disciple* (vv. 26, 27, 33). Discipleship requires comparative loyalty so total that family love and self-love look like *hate* by comparison (v. 26 — Semitic hyperbole, cf. Genesis 29:31, Matthew 10:37); it requires bearing one's *cross* (v. 27 — a deliberately violent image in a Roman-occupied province where crucifixions were public); it requires *renouncing all one's possessions* (v. 33 — *apotasso*, formal taking leave). Between the second and third *cannot* sit the twin parables of the tower-builder and the king (vv. 28-32): both shame the man who commits without calculation. Jesus does not want crowds He cannot keep; He wants disciples who have *sat down* and reckoned. The chapter closes with salt (vv. 34-35) — the disciple who loses his distinctive savor is useless even for the manure pile and is thrown out. *He who has ears to hear, let him hear.*"
